  "ARTICLE_BODY": "Many people believe that a perfectly regular heartbeat is the sign of a healthy heart. However, medical experts are discovering that heart rate variability (HRV) - the slight variations in time between heartbeats - may actually be a better indicator of cardiovascular health. A healthy heart doesn't beat like a metronome; instead, it constantly adjusts its rhythm in response to breathing, stress levels, and physical activity. High HRV typically indicates a well-functioning autonomic nervous system and good cardiovascular fitness. Athletes often have higher HRV than sedentary individuals. Low HRV, on the other hand, can be associated with stress, fatigue, or underlying health issues. Modern fitness trackers and smartwatches now measure HRV to help users monitor their recovery and stress levels. This technology allows people to better understand their body's response to exercise, sleep, and daily stressors, leading to more informed decisions about health and wellness.",
